quran[21]{c,v,t,f}:
54,7,"with down-cast eyes {1} they shall go forth from their graves, {2} as though they were scattered locusts.",footnotes:1:Literally: Their looks will be downcast. This can have several meanings:|181756:(1) That they will appear terror-stricken.
54,8,"They shall be hurrying forth towards the caller, and the unbelievers (who had once denied this Day), will say: “This is a woeful Day.”"
54,9,"Before them Noah's people also gave the lie (to his Message). {1} They rejected Our servant as a liar, saying: “He is a madman”; and he was rebuffed. {2}",footnotes:1:That is
54,10,"Then he called upon His Lord: “Verily I am vanquished; so come You to my aid.”"
54,11,"Thereupon We opened the gates of the sky for water to pour down,"
54,12,"and We made the earth burst forth with springs, {1} and all this water converged to fulfil that which had been decreed.",footnotes:1:That is
54,13,"And We bore Noah on the vessel built of planks and nails, {1}",footnotes:1:This signifies the Ark which the Prophet Noah had built under Allah’s care and guidance even before the coming of the Flood.
54,14,"which sailed on under Our supervision: a reward for him who had been shown ingratitude. {1}",footnotes:1:Literally: This was a vengeance for the sake of him whose kufr had been committed. If kufr be taken in the sense of denial
54,15,"And We left the Ark as a Sign. {1} Is there, then, any who will take heed?",footnotes:1:It may also mean: We left this dreadful punishment as a sign of warning
54,16,"So how awesome were My chastisement and My warnings!"
54,17,"We have made this Qur'an easy as a reminder. {1} Is there, then, any who will take heed?",footnotes:1:Some people have misconstrued the words yassarnal- Quran to mean that the Quran is an easy Book; no knowledge is required to understand it so much so that a person even without the knowledge of the Arabic language
54,18,"'Ad also gave the lie (to Hud). So how awesome were My chastisement and My warnings!"
54,19,"We sent a tumultuous wind against them on a day of unremitting misfortune, {1}",footnotes:1:That is
54,20,"which tore people away and hurled them as though they were trunks of uprooted palm-trees."
54,21,"So how awesome were My chastisement and My warnings!"
54,22,"We have made the Qur'an easy to derive lessons from. Is there, then, any who will take heed?"
54,23,"Thamud gave the lie to the warnings,"
54,24,"saying: “Are we to follow a single mortal, {1} one from among ourselves? If we do that, we shall surely be in error and folly.",footnotes:1:In other words
54,25,"Was there none but he to whom the Reminder could be vouchsafed excluding all others? Nay; he is an insolent liar.” {1}",footnotes:1:The word ashir of the original means a conceited
54,26,"(We told Our Messenger): “Tomorrow they shall know who is the insolent liar."
54,27,"We shall send the she-camel as a trial for them; so watch their end with patience."
